resulted in his spending decades in some of America's most notorious prisons, including four and a half years on death row for a murder López insists he did not commit. To Alcatraz, Death Row, and Back is the personal life story of a man who refused to be broken by either an abusive father or an equally abusive criminal justice system. While López freely admits that "I've been no angel," his insider's account of daily life in Alcatraz and San Quentin graphically reveals the violence, arbitrary infliction of excessive punishment, and unending monotony that give rise to gang cultures within the prisons and practically insure that parolees will commit far worse crimes when they return to the streets. Rafael Pérez-Torres discusses how Ernie López's experiences typify the harsher treatment that ethnic and minority suspects often receive in the American criminal justice system, as well as how they reveal the indomitable resilience of Chicanos/as and their culture. As Pérez-Torres concludes, "López's story presents us with the voice of one who—though subjected to a system meant to destroy his soul—not only endured but survived, and in surviving prevailed."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aDeath row inmateszCaliforniavBiography. 0aHispanic AmericanszCaliforniavBiography. 0aRecidivistszCaliforniavBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh1 aPérez-Torres, Rafael, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Texas Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311074534440uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/70660640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292797024423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292797024/original  a978-3-11-074534-4  University of Texas Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA